1. Use tidycensus to download 1. race/ethnicity (B03002) and 2. median household income for Baltimore City. Store this data in a new object. Choose which race/ethnicity youd like to relate to income (Non-Hispanic Black and Non-Hispanic White work best). Which census tract has the highest percentage of your target race/ethnicity (and what is the percent) and which has the highest median household income (and how much is it?)? (5 points) Reminder: Since we will be mapping our data, make sure you include use geometry = TRUE in get_acs()

#Obtain data from tidycensus
##race/ethnicity 2019
white_pop_2019 <- get_acs(geography = 'tract', #obtain data in census tracts
                                      variables = c('total_pop' = 'B03002_001', #total population
                                                    'white_pop' = 'B03002_003' #non-hispanic white population

                                      survey = 'acs5',
                                      state = c(24), #24 for maryland
                                      county = c(510), #Baltimore city
                                      geometry = TRUE, #download geometry
                                      output = 'wide')

#create a new variable for percentage

#filter to find max
white_pop_2019 %>% filter(percentage_white>90)

2. Please reproject this data to Web Mercator. (1 points)

pop_web <- st_transform(white_pop_2019, 3857)
income_web <- st_transform(white_income_2019, 3857)

3. Create two plots. In the first plot highlight the tract with the highest concentration of your selected race/eth. In the second plot highlight the tract with the highest median household income? (5 points)

#plot the tracts with the highest percentage of white population
pop_web %>% 
  filter(percentage_white > 90) %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data = pop_web) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = percentage_white)) + 
  theme_bw() + 
  ggtitle("Census Tract in Baltimore City with highest percentage of White Population") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 10)) +
  xlab("Longitude") + ylab("Latitude")

#plot the tracts with the highest household income
income_web %>% 
  filter(incomeE > 200000) %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data = income_web) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = incomeE)) + 
  theme_bw() + 
  ggtitle("Census Tract in Baltimore City with the Highest Median Household Income Amongst White Houseowners") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 8)) +
  xlab("Longitude") + ylab("Latitude")

5. Create a bivariate map with your data. (3 points)

map <- ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = biclass_pop_income, mapping = aes(fill = bi_class), color = "white", size = 0.1, show.legend = FALSE) + 
  bi_scale_fill(pal = "DkBlue", dim = 3) +
  labs(
    title = "Race and Income Baltimore City, MD",
    subtitle = "Dark Blue (DkBlue) Palette"
  ) +
  bi_theme() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size=12)) +
  theme(plot.subtitle = element_text(size=10))
plot(map)

6. Use the cowplot package and ggdraw, like in the tutorial to add a legend (2 points).

legend <- bi_legend(pal = "DkBlue",
                    dim = 3,
                    xlab = "Higher % White ",
                    ylab = "Higher Income ",
                    size = 6)

# combine map with legend
finalPlot <- ggdraw() +
  draw_plot(map, 0, 0, 1, 1) +
  draw_plot(legend, 0.2, .05, 0.2, 0.2)

# plot variable containing map and legend
plot(finalPlot)

3. Reflection (3 points)

This assignment was very helpful in continuing to learn to code and process in R. Particularly the use of the biclass tool and the bivariate legend tool. The use of those tools and turning them into a map was also helpful in furthering my ability to create presentable data in R.

I am confident with the tidycensus code, but would like to keep working with the plotting and legend tools to continue to display my maps in an efficient manner

The trickiest part for this lab was making the bivariate color scheme line up. I had to experiment with different styles and diffrent splits to make the data displayable. I also had some trouble filtering out maximums in data sets, but was able to find the results by filtering by a threshold to get a fewer number of outputs first.
